\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
In the writing subdirectory, place your assignment.
 For the first part, read Hansen’s paper in the articles directory of the
 main class github entitled “Hansen AER”.
 Briefly summarize this paper.
 What is his question? What data does he use? What is his research design?
 What does he find.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
This paper analize how driviers who have received punishment for being driving
 under the influence (DUI) are less likely to reincid in tdriving drunk
 as the higher their blood alcohol control (BAC) score was at the moment
 of the penalty.
 Hansen (2015) uses administrative records from the Washington State Impaired
 Driver Testing Program, 1999–2007.
 By using a regression discontinuity approach, Hansen (2015) analizes the
 two BAC triggers cut-offs 0.08 and 0.015 into the reincidence of drunk drivers.
 Hansen (2015) finds evidence that suggest the effectiveness of punishments
 and sanctions in reducing recidivism among drunk drivers.
 The paper also shows that having a BAC over the 0.15 higher punishment limit
 reduces in 1 percentage point repeating drunk driving.
 I find evidence that 10 percent increase in sanctions and punish- ments
 is associated with a 2.3 percent decline in drunk driving.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section*
\paragraph_spacing single
\noindent

\size normal
Replication (worth 6 points).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
In the United States, an officer can arrest a driver if after giving them
 a blood alcohol content test they learn the driver had a BAC of 0.08 or
 higher.
 We will only focus on the 0.08 BAC cutoff.
 We will be ignoring the 0.15 cutoff for all this analysis.
 Create a dummy equaling 1 if bac1>= 0.08 and 0 otherwise in your do file
 or R file.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
gen select=bac1>= 0.08
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
The first thing to do in any RDD is look at the raw data and see if there’s
 any evidence for manipulation.
 If people were capable of manipulating their blood alcohol content (bac1),
 describe the test we would use to check for this.
 Now evaluate whether you see this in these data? Recreate Figure 1 using
 the bac1 variable as your measure of blood alcohol content.
 Do you find evidence for sorting on the running variable? .
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Basically we have to look for a bumps before or after the cut line that
 show manipulation.
 In the replication the value to replicate the chart is width=.0001 no width=0.001
 as showed in the paper.
 There is not an evident manipulation or bump before the cut-off, after
 the cut off is easy to see an small bump.
 This is consistent with the value of the 
\end_layout

